<body>
<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>
<p>Part of a <rs type="material">white marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">plinth</rs> for <rs type="objectType">statuary</rs>, of which the <rs type="decoration">webbed foot of a bird</rs> survives (<measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">0.23</measure>   × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">0.175</measure>   × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="depth">0.04</measure>).</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="text">
<head>Description of Text</head>
<p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> on one face, on a raised panel (<measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">0.09</measure>   × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">0.03</measure>).</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="letters">
<head>Letters</head>
<p><measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height" precision="circa">0.01</measure>; lunate sigma, epsilon, cursive mu.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="date">
<head>Date</head>
<p>
<date notAfter="0300" notBefore="0001" exact="none">First to third centuries A.D.</date>
(<rs type="criteria">lettering</rs>)</p>
</div>
<div type="edition" lang="grc">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab><lb n="1"/><persName type="aphrodisian"><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="left"/>σιμος</name></persName>  <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Ἀρτεμίδωρος">Ἀρτ<unclear reason="damage">εμ</unclear><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ιδώρου</supplied></name></persName>  <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="right"/>  <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="left"/><orig n="unresolved">παν</orig>  <g type="stop"/> <w lemma="ὁ">τῆς</w> <orig n="unresolved"><unclear reason="damage">ο</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="right"/>  </ab>
</div>
<div type="apparatus">
<head>Apparatus</head>
<p>l. 1,  the first name could very well be Ζώσιμος; the second, presumably the patronymic, might well be Ἀρτεμίδωρος (very common at Aphrodisias), but Ἀρτέμων cannot be ruled out.</p><p>l. 2, ? ΤΙΑΝ</p>

</div>
<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>[...] [-]simos ? son of Artem[idoros] [...]</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>This text probably names the man who commissioned or dedicated  the sculpture.</p>
</div>
